7364070637045828907.video_description: Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene (R-GA) on Wednesday vowed to force a vote next week on Speaker Mike Johnson’s (R-LA) ouster, setting up a scenario in which Democrats will provide the votes needed to save a Republican speaker’s job.   “I think the American people need to see a recorded vote,” the Georgia firebrand told reporters. “I think every member of Congress needs to take that vote and let the chips fall where they may.”   Hardline Republicans have grown increasingly frustrated with Speaker Johnson, pointing to him frequently turning to Democrats for their support in passing key legislation like Ukraine aid, government funding and FISA warrantless surveillance.   “Mike Johnson is giving them everything they want,” Rep. Greene said. “I find it very satisfying that they are ready to vote for Mike Johnson. And you want to know something? I want to see it happen.”   Rep. Greene initially filed her motion to vacate last month, but held off on triggering a vote, trying to use it as leverage to wield influence over the speaker. When she makes the motion “privileged” next week, it will require the House to act on it within two legislative days.   The House will likely vote on a motion to table the motion to vacate, which will require a simple majority to shelve the effort.   So far, only two other Republicans have joined Rep. Greene’s effort — Reps. Thomas Massie (KY) and Paul Gosar (AZ) — but given the GOP’s very slim majority, that would likely be enough to strip the speaker of his gavel absent Democratic support.   House Democratic leaders on Tuesday announced they would vote to table the motion, saying it was time to “turn the page” on the chaos in the House that’s been driven by the hardline faction of the Republican conference.   Rep. Greene acknowledged her motion is likely to fail but said it would serve to get lawmakers on record.   “If this vote fails and the whole conference, the whole Congress, supports the ‘uniparty,’ let me tell you something, that is not a failure, it’s a win for the American people because that’s a list of names,” she said.   #marjorietaylorgreene #speakerofthehouse #mikejohnson #cspan

Kennedy and sister of RFK Jr. — called President Biden her “hero” as she rattled off a list of his accomplishments in office.   “We want to make crystal clear our feeling that the best way forward for America is to reelect Joe Biden and Kamala Harris to four more years,” she said at the campaign event in Philadelphia on Thursday.   Prominent members of the Kennedy family have rejected RFK Jr.’s candidacy and disavowed some of his more controversial positions, particularly his anti-vaccine rhetoric.   Ms. Kennedy did not mention her brother by name but said “there are only two candidates with any chance of winning the presidency.”   RFK Jr. noted the endorsement on social media and said he is “pleased” his relatives are politically active, calling it a “family tradition.”   “We are divided in our opinions but united in our love for each other,” he wrote on X. “I hold this as a possibility for America too. Can we disagree without hating our opponents? Can we restore civility and respect to public discourse? I think we can.”   RFK Jr. is the strongest of the third-party and independent candidates, and while he stands no chance of being elected, both the Biden and Trump campaigns fear he could siphon votes from them in key states in November.
